name: Puma concolor (Linnaeus, 1771)
occurrenceRemarks: From TPWD biologists: MOUNTAIN LION in Taylor County: About a week ago, we had the opportunity to examine a mountain lion that had been shot on private property. According to tooth wear characteristics, this male lion was estimated to be between 2-4 years old. This is the third young male lion in 2 years that biologists have examined in this area. At roughly 2 years old, mt. lions reach adulthood, leave their mother and set out to find their own territory. Some have been known to travel hundreds of miles in the process. As part of ongoing efforts to study and monitor mountain lion populations across the state, TPWD biologist welcome legitimate reports of recent mt. lion sightings. Taking measurements and tissue samples can help us answer questions about where they came from, what they are eating, and any potential disease issues they could be experiencing. While reports of animals seen weeks or years in the past are interesting, the sighting must be within a day or two to be useful. If you get pictures of a mt lion, find one dead on the road, or happen to harvest one while hunting, we would love to get as much information as possible. For more info about mt lions or to find out where to report a sighting go to http://bit.ly/MountainLionsTX *posting by Sam Kieschnick, TPWD urban wildlife biologist (@sambiology)

occurrenceRemarks: This camera is at my horse trough five feet from my house. I think the third set of eyes belong to a Grey Fox. He walked in 2 minutes after last lion pic. After reviewing pictures and time stamps I now think it was a female with two cubs. The fox came in 2 1/2 minutes after.

verbatimLocality: San Pasqual Valley, San Diego, CA, USA
name: Puma concolor (Linnaeus, 1771)
occurrenceRemarks: Several weathered tracks, associated. Under interstate 15 bridge over San Dieguito River. Broken trail. Where possible, I was able to measure stride lengths of 21 - 25 inches, but not considered reliable. Tracking community will see why I've stopped short of identifying these to species. I have some hesitation. Peer review, please! [ Thanks to all for confirming what I'd decided in the field for these ]
